subsection.p:
To obtain  acceleration  at a particular instant  t ,  we seek average acceleration in an infinitesimal interval near the instant  t . This leads to the ratio in Eq.  becoming a derivative.

	\vec a  = \dfrac{d \vec v}{dt}.

We can express the Cartesian components of acceleration as derivatives of the corresponding Cartesian components of the velocity vector.

	 \amp a_x = \dfrac{dv_x}{dt}
	 \amp a_y = \dfrac{dv_y}{dt}
	 \amp a_z = \dfrac{dv_z}{dt}

Since  v_x = dx/dt ,  v_y = dy/dt , snd  v_z = dz/dt , we find that we can express components of acceleration as second derivatives of the position.

	 \amp a_x = \dfrac{d^2x}{dt^2}
	 \amp a_y = \dfrac{d^2y}{dt^2}
	 \amp a_z = \dfrac{d^2z}{dt^2}

This is often written compactly as

	\vec a = \dfrac{d^2\vec r}{dt^2}.
